    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-29T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-29T12:00:00-05:00" n="274"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d274">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 EW/7–2944: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-29T20:00:00+03:00"
                            >July 29, 1944—8 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received July 30—3:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>2806. I left with Vyshinski<note n="95" xml:id="d274fn95">Andrey Yanuaryevich
                        Vyshinsky, Assistant People’s Commissar for Foreign Affairs of the Soviet
                        Union.</note> today and [<hi rend="italic">an</hi>] <hi rend="italic"
                        >aide-mémoire</hi> containing the substance of the Department’s 1783, July
                    27, 2 p.m.<note n="96" xml:id="d274fn96">Not printed; it summarized Bulgarian
                        reports in telegrams from Istanbul (740.00119 E.W./7–2744).</note> In reply
                        <pb facs="0366" n="354" xml:id="pg_354"/> to my inquiries Vyshinski stated
                    that the Soviet Government had received no recent information on the situation
                    in Bulgaria and that, although he wished to study carefully the <hi
                        rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi>, it was difficult for him to say at this
                    time how seriously the Bulgarian statements should be taken.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Harriman</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
